Aerobiology, the study of living organisms and their components in air, became a full-fledged scientific discipline in 1964. This was followed in 1974 by the founding of the International Association of Aerobiology (https://sites.google.com/site/aerobiologyinternational/). The initial focus of this group was the study and movement of pollen, but microbes and other life forms were soon added to the mix with a corresponding broadening of the organization's scope (Fig 1
). The microbiologic quality of indoor air comes under the rubric of aerobiology (Fig 2
). This workshop will focus only on indoor air as a vehicle for human pathogens.
